WEBVTT
Kind: captions
Language: en

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:03.381
[MUSIC PLAYING]

00:00:05.744 --> 00:00:07.910
NATHAN RUNKLE: So today, I
want to talk a little bit

00:00:07.910 --> 00:00:11.540
about my story, founding
Mercy for Animals, the work

00:00:11.540 --> 00:00:14.600
that we do to give
farmed animals a voice

00:00:14.600 --> 00:00:18.050
on an international level,
why animals even matter,

00:00:18.050 --> 00:00:23.320
and what the future of our
food system can look like.

00:00:23.320 --> 00:00:25.510
So I guess you could
say it makes sense

00:00:25.510 --> 00:00:28.330
that I would start an
international animal rights

00:00:28.330 --> 00:00:30.670
organization given the
fact that I was actually

00:00:30.670 --> 00:00:32.930
delivered by a veterinarian.

00:00:32.930 --> 00:00:38.470
My dad, Mark, who you see
illegally driving around

00:00:38.470 --> 00:00:41.440
with me in this photograph,
was a veterinarian,

00:00:41.440 --> 00:00:43.300
graduated from OSU.

00:00:43.300 --> 00:00:46.870
And I was born on
the couch at home

00:00:46.870 --> 00:00:50.260
in a village of less than
2,000 people in rural Ohio.

00:00:50.260 --> 00:00:54.220
So I was slated to be a
fifth generation farmer,

00:00:54.220 --> 00:00:58.000
but my love for animals
and fascination for animals

00:00:58.000 --> 00:01:01.420
would lead me on a
very different path.

00:01:01.420 --> 00:01:04.780
Now, they say that big lessons
can come in small packages,

00:01:04.780 --> 00:01:07.510
and that was definitely
the case for me.

00:01:07.510 --> 00:01:12.700
And that little package
was a rat named Cesar.

00:01:12.700 --> 00:01:16.450
When I was six years old, I
went across the cornfields

00:01:16.450 --> 00:01:20.950
from our house to a couple
whose name was Gene and Sylvia,

00:01:20.950 --> 00:01:26.500
and they actually raised animals
for research in laboratories.

00:01:26.500 --> 00:01:30.310
They raised rabbits, mice,
rats, and guinea pigs,

00:01:30.310 --> 00:01:32.544
and they rented the
property from my parents.

00:01:32.544 --> 00:01:34.210
And one afternoon
when I went over there

00:01:34.210 --> 00:01:36.760
with my mom to collect
that month's rent check,

00:01:36.760 --> 00:01:39.890
Sylvia asked if I wanted to
see the animals because she

00:01:39.890 --> 00:01:41.140
knew of my deep love for them.

00:01:41.140 --> 00:01:42.777
And I said, yes, of course.

00:01:42.777 --> 00:01:44.110
She took me inside of the sheds.

00:01:44.110 --> 00:01:47.770
And now I really look back in
horror at what I saw there.

00:01:47.770 --> 00:01:51.070
These animals crammed in
tiny cages, dead animals

00:01:51.070 --> 00:01:53.980
in the corners, the
smell of ammonia.

00:01:53.980 --> 00:01:55.420
She reached into
one of the cages

00:01:55.420 --> 00:01:57.850
and pulled this white
rat out by his tail

00:01:57.850 --> 00:02:01.330
and lowered him into my
hands, and I begged her

00:02:01.330 --> 00:02:03.160
to allow me to take him home.

00:02:03.160 --> 00:02:04.810
And she said yes.

00:02:04.810 --> 00:02:06.010
My mother said yes.

00:02:06.010 --> 00:02:07.780
And I named this
little guy Cesar.

00:02:07.780 --> 00:02:11.309
And he became my best friend
for about 2 and 1/2 years.

00:02:11.309 --> 00:02:13.600
He would sit on my shoulder
as I went around the house.

00:02:13.600 --> 00:02:16.810
He knew his name.

00:02:16.810 --> 00:02:18.850
He would come running
when I called him.

00:02:18.850 --> 00:02:22.810
And I realized just how
intelligent and social

00:02:22.810 --> 00:02:24.010
these animals are.

00:02:24.010 --> 00:02:26.950
How they have their own
unique personalities.

00:02:26.950 --> 00:02:30.400
But Cesar also taught
me about the prejudices

00:02:30.400 --> 00:02:33.100
that humans bring to the
table with certain animals.

00:02:33.100 --> 00:02:36.160
And he started to peel back
the layers of my own view,

00:02:36.160 --> 00:02:38.590
as a young child,
about what separates

00:02:38.590 --> 00:02:41.200
animals that we consider
to be pests from those

00:02:41.200 --> 00:02:43.840
that we consider to
be pets, and those

00:02:43.840 --> 00:02:47.980
that we consider friends and
those that we consider food.

00:02:47.980 --> 00:02:52.240
I would take friends and
friends' parents to see Cesar,

00:02:52.240 --> 00:02:56.070
and so many of them would shriek
in horror and disgust, saying,

00:02:56.070 --> 00:02:56.770
ew, a rat.

00:02:56.770 --> 00:02:58.360
Look at his tail.

00:02:58.360 --> 00:03:01.660
They didn't know him as
an individual as I did.

00:03:01.660 --> 00:03:08.070
They were judging Cesar for
what he was, not who he was.

00:03:08.070 --> 00:03:10.430
I started to realize
from Cesar that when

00:03:10.430 --> 00:03:12.110
it comes to having
personalities,

00:03:12.110 --> 00:03:14.330
and minds, and interests,
and a spark for life,

00:03:14.330 --> 00:03:17.030
that all animals
are really equal,

00:03:17.030 --> 00:03:20.210
and the difference is only
our perception of them.

00:03:20.210 --> 00:03:24.830
About six years later, another
big, life changing lesson

00:03:24.830 --> 00:03:29.750
came in also a small package,
and that was a baby piglet.

00:03:29.750 --> 00:03:32.330
My local high school in
this farming community

00:03:32.330 --> 00:03:34.220
had an agriculture class.

00:03:34.220 --> 00:03:38.384
And the teacher of that class,
Mr. Jenkins, was a pig farmer.

00:03:38.384 --> 00:03:39.800
And it came time
in the curriculum

00:03:39.800 --> 00:03:42.230
where they were going to
do a dissection project,

00:03:42.230 --> 00:03:45.020
and Mr. Jenkins decided
that he would kill some baby

00:03:45.020 --> 00:03:46.190
piglets on his farm.

00:03:46.190 --> 00:03:49.520
He raised over 10,000
pigs, a large operation.

00:03:49.520 --> 00:03:52.760
He arrived one May
morning in 1999

00:03:52.760 --> 00:03:56.330
with this bucket of
piglets to the classroom,

00:03:56.330 --> 00:04:01.090
and when he got there, one of
the piglets was still alive.

00:04:01.090 --> 00:04:03.790
A student in the class, who did
part-time work on Mr. Jenkins'

00:04:03.790 --> 00:04:07.420
farm, walked over to the
bucket, picked up this piglet

00:04:07.420 --> 00:04:12.800
by her hind legs, and slammed
her head first into the ground.

00:04:12.800 --> 00:04:16.410
Now, this piglet, which
you see right here

00:04:16.410 --> 00:04:18.970
in these photographs,
didn't die.

00:04:18.970 --> 00:04:20.769
She was determined to survive.

00:04:20.769 --> 00:04:21.839
Her skull was fractured.

00:04:21.839 --> 00:04:23.255
She was bleeding
out of her mouth.

00:04:23.255 --> 00:04:25.650
She was vocalizing in distress.

00:04:25.650 --> 00:04:28.290
A few students, who were
just absolutely appalled

00:04:28.290 --> 00:04:29.970
by what they had
witnessed, grabbed

00:04:29.970 --> 00:04:32.880
this now dying animal,
left the classroom,

00:04:32.880 --> 00:04:35.945
went down the hallway to
Molly Fearing's classroom--

00:04:35.945 --> 00:04:37.320
another teacher
in the school who

00:04:37.320 --> 00:04:39.180
was known as being
the vegetarian who

00:04:39.180 --> 00:04:40.750
cared about animals.

00:04:40.750 --> 00:04:43.350
She left the school, went
to a local veterinarian,

00:04:43.350 --> 00:04:45.810
and had this poor
piglet euthanized.

00:04:45.810 --> 00:04:48.690
There was nothing they
could do to help her.

00:04:48.690 --> 00:04:52.230
Molly's next stop was the
local Sheriff's department

00:04:52.230 --> 00:04:55.020
where she filed an
animal cruelty complaint,

00:04:55.020 --> 00:04:58.530
asking that charges be
brought, and they were.

00:04:58.530 --> 00:05:00.090
The very first
day of that trial,

00:05:00.090 --> 00:05:03.500
however, the cruelty
charges were dismissed.

00:05:03.500 --> 00:05:05.730
And that's because in
Ohio, like most states,

00:05:05.730 --> 00:05:09.450
if something is considered
standard agricultural practice,

00:05:09.450 --> 00:05:11.840
it's exempt from
cruelty prosecution.

00:05:11.840 --> 00:05:14.310
And the practice of slamming
baby piglets head first

00:05:14.310 --> 00:05:17.640
into the ground is considered
standard agricultural practice,

00:05:17.640 --> 00:05:20.100
known as thumping in
the pork industry.

00:05:20.100 --> 00:05:23.310
It is considered a
cheap and effective way

00:05:23.310 --> 00:05:25.410
of killing animals.

00:05:25.410 --> 00:05:28.440
Now this case, to
me as a 15-year-old,

00:05:28.440 --> 00:05:30.270
illustrated that
there needed to be

00:05:30.270 --> 00:05:33.120
an organization in my
local farming community

00:05:33.120 --> 00:05:36.270
that would advocate on
behalf of these animals.

00:05:36.270 --> 00:05:41.070
It was clear to me, had
this been a puppy or kitten,

00:05:41.070 --> 00:05:43.500
the outcome would have
been completely different.

00:05:43.500 --> 00:05:45.530
The cruelty charges
would have stuck,

00:05:45.530 --> 00:05:49.260
and the teacher would
have been referred

00:05:49.260 --> 00:05:51.840
for psychiatric
evaluation, perhaps banned

00:05:51.840 --> 00:05:54.150
from ever having animals again.

00:05:54.150 --> 00:06:01.490
But because it was a pig, the
outcome was very different.

00:06:01.490 --> 00:06:03.510
So I started Mercy for Animals.

00:06:03.510 --> 00:06:05.330
We had no money, no resources.

00:06:05.330 --> 00:06:07.100
I had no idea what
I was doing, but I

00:06:07.100 --> 00:06:09.590
had a passion to right
a wrong and give a voice

00:06:09.590 --> 00:06:11.510
to these animals who suffer.

00:06:11.510 --> 00:06:15.380
Today, Mercy for Animals works
in four main program areas.

00:06:15.380 --> 00:06:17.810
The first, undercover
investigation-- sending people

00:06:17.810 --> 00:06:20.000
into factory farms
and slaughterhouses,

00:06:20.000 --> 00:06:21.920
wired with pinhole-sized
hidden cameras,

00:06:21.920 --> 00:06:25.100
to document what takes
place behind the closed

00:06:25.100 --> 00:06:27.320
doors of industrial
factory farms,

00:06:27.320 --> 00:06:30.260
hatcheries, livestock auctions,
when the industry doesn't

00:06:30.260 --> 00:06:32.060
think that it is being watched.

00:06:32.060 --> 00:06:34.560
And I'll talk more
about that later.

00:06:34.560 --> 00:06:38.210
We also work through legal
advocacy, changing laws,

00:06:38.210 --> 00:06:40.850
pushing on a federal level,
but also on a state level

00:06:40.850 --> 00:06:43.680
to outlaw the worst
factory farm practices.

00:06:43.680 --> 00:06:45.830
Through corporate outreach,
pushing the largest

00:06:45.830 --> 00:06:48.350
corporations in this country--
everyone from Wal-Mart

00:06:48.350 --> 00:06:51.680
to McDonald's-- to also abandon
the cruelest factory farm

00:06:51.680 --> 00:06:52.380
practices.

00:06:52.380 --> 00:06:55.250
And finally, through consumer
education and awareness

00:06:55.250 --> 00:06:56.120
campaigns--

00:06:56.120 --> 00:06:58.220
informing people on
the fact that animals

00:06:58.220 --> 00:07:00.890
are individuals with unique
minds and personalities.

00:07:00.890 --> 00:07:02.630
Their lives matter,
the treatment of them

00:07:02.630 --> 00:07:06.050
matters, and that our
food choices also matter.

00:07:06.050 --> 00:07:08.919
And moving towards a vegan
diet, moving away from animals

00:07:08.919 --> 00:07:09.710
and towards plants.

00:07:12.270 --> 00:07:15.750
This incident taught
me at a young age

00:07:15.750 --> 00:07:19.260
that we all have power.

00:07:19.260 --> 00:07:20.940
Just the fact that
we were born human

00:07:20.940 --> 00:07:22.650
puts us in a place of power.

00:07:22.650 --> 00:07:25.050
To be in a time
and a country where

00:07:25.050 --> 00:07:30.510
we are able to speak
freely also gives us power.

00:07:30.510 --> 00:07:32.250
And Mercy for
Animals has been one

00:07:32.250 --> 00:07:34.620
of the most empowering
experiences of my life,

00:07:34.620 --> 00:07:38.460
being able to advocate on
those who have no voice.

00:07:38.460 --> 00:07:40.200
Dr. King once said
that our lives

00:07:40.200 --> 00:07:44.310
begin to end the day that we
become silent about things

00:07:44.310 --> 00:07:46.164
that matter.

00:07:46.164 --> 00:07:47.580
So I want to talk
about people who

00:07:47.580 --> 00:07:51.420
are using their place of power
to help animals and speak out

00:07:51.420 --> 00:07:53.790
about things that matter.

00:07:53.790 --> 00:07:57.210
One such individual
is Dr. Jane Goodall.

00:07:57.210 --> 00:07:58.800
Now she says, we
have to understand

00:07:58.800 --> 00:08:01.470
that we are not the only
beings on this planet

00:08:01.470 --> 00:08:03.470
with personalities and minds.

00:08:03.470 --> 00:08:06.600
Now, most of us are at least
somewhat familiar with the work

00:08:06.600 --> 00:08:10.050
of Dr. Goodall, who
spent over 40 years

00:08:10.050 --> 00:08:14.130
living with and observing
chimpanzees in Africa.

00:08:14.130 --> 00:08:16.740
Now, she started to do
this work at a time when

00:08:16.740 --> 00:08:20.700
even the veterinary community
was not united in the belief

00:08:20.700 --> 00:08:24.360
and understanding that all
animals felt physical pain, let

00:08:24.360 --> 00:08:27.060
alone that they had rich
intellectual and emotional

00:08:27.060 --> 00:08:28.170
lives.

00:08:28.170 --> 00:08:30.810
It was through
Dr. Goodall's work

00:08:30.810 --> 00:08:34.380
that we started to understand
that many of the false barriers

00:08:34.380 --> 00:08:36.059
and walls that we
put up between us

00:08:36.059 --> 00:08:38.580
and other animals were,
in fact, non-existent.

00:08:38.580 --> 00:08:41.760
She witnessed and
documented animals

00:08:41.760 --> 00:08:47.070
having culture, having
language, using tools, grieving

00:08:47.070 --> 00:08:48.810
for the loss of loved ones.

00:08:51.570 --> 00:08:56.240
This is an image that I think
really shows friendship,

00:08:56.240 --> 00:08:58.130
and loyalty, and love.

00:08:58.130 --> 00:09:01.210
These are two dogs in China.

00:09:01.210 --> 00:09:03.080
Now, they were street dogs.

00:09:03.080 --> 00:09:05.470
They never had a
human companion.

00:09:05.470 --> 00:09:07.730
They were never given
names by people.

00:09:07.730 --> 00:09:11.450
But to each other,
they meant everything.

00:09:11.450 --> 00:09:14.690
One afternoon,
the female was hit

00:09:14.690 --> 00:09:17.570
and she was killed by a car.

00:09:17.570 --> 00:09:22.520
Her loyal companion stayed
by her side for hours on end,

00:09:22.520 --> 00:09:27.650
licking her face, nudging her,
dodging traffic to comfort her.

00:09:27.650 --> 00:09:32.600
This is, of course, just
one example of that bond.

00:09:32.600 --> 00:09:35.120
And we live in a
country where half of us

00:09:35.120 --> 00:09:37.310
share our homes
with dogs and cats.

00:09:37.310 --> 00:09:39.200
And of those
animals, half of them

00:09:39.200 --> 00:09:42.030
will receive gifts
this holiday season.

00:09:42.030 --> 00:09:44.810
We spend billions of
dollars on their care

00:09:44.810 --> 00:09:49.220
and toys and medical procedures,
yet we live in a country

00:09:49.220 --> 00:09:52.160
where billions, literally
billions of animals

00:09:52.160 --> 00:09:54.590
suffer and die the
worst fate imaginable.

00:09:54.590 --> 00:09:57.590
And those, of course,
are farmed animals.

00:09:57.590 --> 00:09:59.240
And part of what
Mercy for Animals does

00:09:59.240 --> 00:10:02.360
is help to bridge the
gap in our empathy

00:10:02.360 --> 00:10:05.150
and our understanding
of animals,

00:10:05.150 --> 00:10:06.860
to widen our circle
of compassion

00:10:06.860 --> 00:10:09.230
to include those that,
for all too long,

00:10:09.230 --> 00:10:13.240
have simply been labeled food.

00:10:13.240 --> 00:10:17.080
This is another image that
tells a story of love.

00:10:17.080 --> 00:10:19.810
This image is from India.

00:10:19.810 --> 00:10:25.420
This mother cow's baby was
hit and killed by a bus.

00:10:25.420 --> 00:10:29.760
For two years, she
stayed in the same area.

00:10:29.760 --> 00:10:32.290
And every time that the bus
that hit and killed her baby

00:10:32.290 --> 00:10:36.460
came by, she would slowly
walk along it in front of it

00:10:36.460 --> 00:10:40.030
as if trying to prevent the bus
from killing any other animals.

00:10:40.030 --> 00:10:43.480
Now, the bus driver became
so frustrated by this

00:10:43.480 --> 00:10:45.790
that he actually
painted the bus trying

00:10:45.790 --> 00:10:49.300
to disguise it and
fool this mother cow,

00:10:49.300 --> 00:10:50.790
but she wasn't fooled.

00:10:50.790 --> 00:10:53.710
She remembered the face
of the man who drove

00:10:53.710 --> 00:10:55.660
the bus that killed her baby.

00:10:55.660 --> 00:11:00.460
So this, of course, shows
not only emotional empathy,

00:11:00.460 --> 00:11:04.490
but also a prolonged
memory as well.

00:11:04.490 --> 00:11:06.970
Now, of course animals
tell us so much

00:11:06.970 --> 00:11:11.620
if we will just bother to
listen and watch and observe.

00:11:11.620 --> 00:11:13.660
And often times, science
is slow to catch up

00:11:13.660 --> 00:11:17.920
with what that would tell us,
but finally, that is happening.

00:11:17.920 --> 00:11:21.940
Just a few years ago, hundreds
of the leading scientists

00:11:21.940 --> 00:11:25.870
signed the Cambridge
Declaration of Consciousness.

00:11:25.870 --> 00:11:28.840
And what this says is
that all animals are just

00:11:28.840 --> 00:11:30.940
as conscious and
aware as humans.

00:11:30.940 --> 00:11:32.650
And we're not just
talking about mammals.

00:11:32.650 --> 00:11:38.160
We're talking about birds,
fish, and even octopus.

00:11:38.160 --> 00:11:40.500
This is a headline
just from the last week

00:11:40.500 --> 00:11:42.210
that appeared in
"The New York Times."

00:11:42.210 --> 00:11:46.150
Fish depression is not a
joke, talking about depression

00:11:46.150 --> 00:11:49.080
in fish in captivity, where
they are kept in enclosures

00:11:49.080 --> 00:11:50.520
with no stimulation.

00:11:50.520 --> 00:11:55.190
So much so that fish are being
used to study antidepressants.

00:11:55.190 --> 00:11:57.860
This article from
"Smithsonian"--

00:11:57.860 --> 00:12:00.240
Fido's making that
puppy face on purpose.

00:12:00.240 --> 00:12:03.640
He's trying to
tell you something.

00:12:03.640 --> 00:12:05.150
And of course, this
all makes sense.

00:12:05.150 --> 00:12:09.580
When we think about our
singular place of life forming,

00:12:09.580 --> 00:12:11.980
of evolution beginning,
it makes sense

00:12:11.980 --> 00:12:14.320
that other animals
would remember

00:12:14.320 --> 00:12:16.690
faces of friends and foes.

00:12:16.690 --> 00:12:17.950
It helps with their survival.

00:12:17.950 --> 00:12:21.460
Bonding and empathy also
helps with their survival.

00:12:21.460 --> 00:12:23.860
Not to mention, of course,
physical pain being

00:12:23.860 --> 00:12:27.010
necessary for their survival.

00:12:27.010 --> 00:12:29.110
But we have grown
so disconnected.

00:12:29.110 --> 00:12:31.960
We start to view ourselves as
different from other animals--

00:12:31.960 --> 00:12:34.120
separate from.

00:12:34.120 --> 00:12:37.210
But only 70,000 years ago,
there are at least six species

00:12:37.210 --> 00:12:39.100
of humans on this Earth--

00:12:39.100 --> 00:12:42.640
Neanderthals, Homo erectus,
[INAUDIBLE],, and others.

00:12:42.640 --> 00:12:44.500
But about 10,000
years ago, things

00:12:44.500 --> 00:12:48.040
started to change as we
domesticated plants and animals

00:12:48.040 --> 00:12:50.830
in the Neolithic period,
and we started agriculture.

00:12:50.830 --> 00:12:54.100
We became stationary rather
than hunter or gatherers.

00:12:54.100 --> 00:12:56.170
And with that, we built walls--

00:12:56.170 --> 00:12:59.140
literal walls-- between
us and the natural world

00:12:59.140 --> 00:13:02.350
and our animal cousins.

00:13:02.350 --> 00:13:04.720
And that agriculture that
once sustained us and allowed

00:13:04.720 --> 00:13:07.630
us to start civilization as
we know it in human history,

00:13:07.630 --> 00:13:11.500
as we know it, has
gone completely awry,

00:13:11.500 --> 00:13:14.380
leading to factory
farms, other animals not

00:13:14.380 --> 00:13:16.450
being viewed as
sentient creatures,

00:13:16.450 --> 00:13:22.790
but as production units,
as machines, as resources.

00:13:22.790 --> 00:13:27.950
And I believe that we must shift
and have an ethical evolution

00:13:27.950 --> 00:13:29.570
that encompasses animals.

00:13:29.570 --> 00:13:32.030
And I think that this
quote from "The Economist"

00:13:32.030 --> 00:13:34.580
sums up that march forward well.

00:13:34.580 --> 00:13:37.250
It says, "Historically,
man has expanded

00:13:37.250 --> 00:13:40.610
the reach of his ethical
calculations, as ignorance

00:13:40.610 --> 00:13:43.850
and wants have receded, first
beyond family and tribe,

00:13:43.850 --> 00:13:46.820
later beyond religion,
race, and nation.

00:13:46.820 --> 00:13:48.470
Bringing other
species more fully

00:13:48.470 --> 00:13:50.960
into the range of
these decisions one day

00:13:50.960 --> 00:13:56.380
may seem no more than
civilized behavior requires."

00:13:56.380 --> 00:14:00.430
And we are starting to see
this ethical march forward

00:14:00.430 --> 00:14:04.960
in our treatment of animals, in
our understanding of animals.

00:14:04.960 --> 00:14:11.080
After over 130 years of
confining elephants, of ripping

00:14:11.080 --> 00:14:14.290
them from their families,
capturing them in the wild,

00:14:14.290 --> 00:14:18.070
of beating tigers, Ringling
Brothers and Barnum and Bailey

00:14:18.070 --> 00:14:21.550
Circus, citing
declining attendance

00:14:21.550 --> 00:14:25.450
and new legal restrictions
against their acts,

00:14:25.450 --> 00:14:29.689
has permanently shut down.

00:14:29.689 --> 00:14:31.730
And we are starting to
see an increased awareness

00:14:31.730 --> 00:14:36.140
of the problems of keeping orcas
and dolphins in confinement

00:14:36.140 --> 00:14:38.750
at places like SeaWorld.

00:14:38.750 --> 00:14:40.490
And I predict in
the next few years,

00:14:40.490 --> 00:14:42.590
we will see similar
announcements

00:14:42.590 --> 00:14:46.460
from SeaWorld and similar
aquatic parks that

00:14:46.460 --> 00:14:51.060
will also retire these animals
to oceanside sanctuaries.

00:14:51.060 --> 00:14:52.860
This just from the
last few weeks--

00:14:52.860 --> 00:14:56.040
California puppy mill ban
will require pet stores

00:14:56.040 --> 00:14:58.560
to sell rescue animals.

00:14:58.560 --> 00:15:00.990
California becoming
the first state

00:15:00.990 --> 00:15:06.450
in the nation to
ban the sale of dogs

00:15:06.450 --> 00:15:11.280
from puppy mills in pet stores,
taking effect in January 2019.

00:15:11.280 --> 00:15:15.840
So there is a march forward
in our treatment of animals.

00:15:15.840 --> 00:15:18.510
But when we talk
about animals, we're

00:15:18.510 --> 00:15:21.530
really talking about
farmed animals,

00:15:21.530 --> 00:15:24.240
though they are the
most absent, the most

00:15:24.240 --> 00:15:26.790
invisible from our scenario.

00:15:26.790 --> 00:15:30.120
We don't go home to
a pig-- most of us.

00:15:30.120 --> 00:15:32.640
We don't share our homes
with them, but most of us

00:15:32.640 --> 00:15:34.540
don't know them as individuals.

00:15:34.540 --> 00:15:39.540
But as this chart shows,
they really are the 99%.

00:15:39.540 --> 00:15:41.910
The yellow, showing the
number of farmed animals

00:15:41.910 --> 00:15:42.990
used in this country.

00:15:42.990 --> 00:15:44.910
The blue, animals and labs.

00:15:44.910 --> 00:15:46.170
Gray, shelters.

00:15:46.170 --> 00:15:48.760
And in black, clothing.

00:15:48.760 --> 00:15:51.080
Nearly 9 billion in
the US every year.

00:15:51.080 --> 00:15:54.370
That's about 300 every second.

00:15:54.370 --> 00:15:56.950
We're looking at
hundreds of billions

00:15:56.950 --> 00:16:00.310
on an international level when
you include aquatic life, which

00:16:00.310 --> 00:16:01.270
of course, we should.

00:16:05.470 --> 00:16:07.030
And this is what
most people really

00:16:07.030 --> 00:16:09.040
know about factory farming--

00:16:09.040 --> 00:16:10.150
very little.

00:16:10.150 --> 00:16:12.010
And that is by design.

00:16:12.010 --> 00:16:13.630
Obviously, there
is so much money

00:16:13.630 --> 00:16:19.090
pumped into portraying this
false image that happy meat

00:16:19.090 --> 00:16:21.490
comes from happy animals.

00:16:21.490 --> 00:16:24.400
We are told, from children, that
hamburgers grow in hamburger

00:16:24.400 --> 00:16:26.620
patches at McDonald's.

00:16:26.620 --> 00:16:29.020
And there is a concerted
effort by the meat industry

00:16:29.020 --> 00:16:31.060
to keep people in
the dark-- in fact,

00:16:31.060 --> 00:16:34.570
criminalize even taking
photographs inside

00:16:34.570 --> 00:16:36.430
of factory farms
and slaughterhouses,

00:16:36.430 --> 00:16:39.430
further pulling
the curtain closed.

00:16:39.430 --> 00:16:41.110
But at Mercy for
Animals, we believe

00:16:41.110 --> 00:16:43.651
that people have a right to know
where their food comes from.

00:16:43.651 --> 00:16:46.480
That animals have a right
to have their stories told.

00:16:46.480 --> 00:16:50.350
And that's why we carry out
undercover investigations.

00:16:50.350 --> 00:16:53.320
And I talk about this
at length in my book,

00:16:53.320 --> 00:16:55.960
but I want to tell you
just a little bit about who

00:16:55.960 --> 00:16:58.930
these incredible
individuals are.

00:16:58.930 --> 00:17:02.020
On the left here is Pete.

00:17:02.020 --> 00:17:04.990
Pete is the most prolific
undercover investigator

00:17:04.990 --> 00:17:07.760
that the American animal
rights movement has ever seen.

00:17:07.760 --> 00:17:11.240
He has been to over
400 puppy mills.

00:17:11.240 --> 00:17:13.240
He has been inside of
dozens of factory farms

00:17:13.240 --> 00:17:15.550
and slaughterhouses, and
now does investigations

00:17:15.550 --> 00:17:17.859
on an international level.

00:17:17.859 --> 00:17:20.109
Liz, who you see
here in the middle,

00:17:20.109 --> 00:17:22.720
used to work at an
animal sanctuary,

00:17:22.720 --> 00:17:26.349
but she knew that if she left
behind her friends and family

00:17:26.349 --> 00:17:27.819
and did undercover
investigation,

00:17:27.819 --> 00:17:29.800
she would be able to
help even more animals.

00:17:29.800 --> 00:17:31.030
And so she did that.

00:17:31.030 --> 00:17:33.760
In fact, her work
at Butterball Turkey

00:17:33.760 --> 00:17:37.420
led to the first ever felony
conviction for cruelty

00:17:37.420 --> 00:17:39.280
to factory farm birds.

00:17:39.280 --> 00:17:43.480
And on the right is Cody, who
is a former investigator who

00:17:43.480 --> 00:17:46.900
has worked at the largest
dairy farm in New York,

00:17:46.900 --> 00:17:48.970
leading to criminal
animal cruelty convictions

00:17:48.970 --> 00:17:52.030
and international policy
change, and at a pig factory

00:17:52.030 --> 00:17:53.880
farm in Pennsylvania.

00:17:53.880 --> 00:17:58.270
And I want to tell you a
story from his work there.

00:17:58.270 --> 00:18:01.360
On his first day at this
breeding facility, where

00:18:01.360 --> 00:18:03.850
pigs are kept locked
in tiny crates

00:18:03.850 --> 00:18:06.880
where they can't turn around,
Cody opened the shed door

00:18:06.880 --> 00:18:07.930
and stepped inside.

00:18:07.930 --> 00:18:11.110
And he saw mother
pigs with their babies

00:18:11.110 --> 00:18:12.970
in farrowing crates.

00:18:12.970 --> 00:18:16.300
But he noticed that one
of the cage doors was open

00:18:16.300 --> 00:18:19.840
and the mother was in the
hallway with her baby piglets

00:18:19.840 --> 00:18:21.640
behind her.

00:18:21.640 --> 00:18:24.610
And as he investigated
more, he realized

00:18:24.610 --> 00:18:28.480
that, in fact, two
other sows were also

00:18:28.480 --> 00:18:32.920
free from their cage and their
piglets following behind.

00:18:32.920 --> 00:18:35.200
Cody asked other workers
what had happened.

00:18:35.200 --> 00:18:37.150
They did some
investigating, and they

00:18:37.150 --> 00:18:41.080
determined that the one
mother sow had figured out

00:18:41.080 --> 00:18:45.430
how to use her tongue to
unlatch a pin in the cage door

00:18:45.430 --> 00:18:50.380
and liberate herself, and then
freed her piglets behind her.

00:18:50.380 --> 00:18:52.210
But she didn't stop there.

00:18:52.210 --> 00:18:54.790
She opened the cage doors
of other suffering pigs

00:18:54.790 --> 00:18:55.840
around her.

00:18:55.840 --> 00:18:57.970
Now, they say that
the definition of love

00:18:57.970 --> 00:19:01.540
is having a benevolent
and unselfish concern

00:19:01.540 --> 00:19:03.490
for the good of another.

00:19:03.490 --> 00:19:06.610
If this isn't an act of
love, I don't know what is.

00:19:06.610 --> 00:19:11.500
It certainly is an act
of bravery and courage.

00:19:11.500 --> 00:19:13.990
Now, how was she
repaid for this?

00:19:13.990 --> 00:19:16.840
She was shot in the head
with a captive bolt gun.

00:19:16.840 --> 00:19:20.930
The farm says that once pigs
learn how to free themselves,

00:19:20.930 --> 00:19:22.970
they will continue to do
it time and time again.

00:19:26.884 --> 00:19:29.300
So that's just one story of
the bravery and courage that's

00:19:29.300 --> 00:19:31.239
happening right now
inside of factory farms.

00:19:31.239 --> 00:19:33.530
We talked about the physical
pain that animals endure--

00:19:33.530 --> 00:19:36.800
and we should-- but there's
also emotional distress

00:19:36.800 --> 00:19:39.290
that these animals are
subjected to as well.

00:19:39.290 --> 00:19:43.640
At Mercy for Animals, we
focus on doing the most good

00:19:43.640 --> 00:19:44.330
that we can.

00:19:44.330 --> 00:19:47.450
We realize that we have limited
time, resources, and energy.

00:19:47.450 --> 00:19:50.930
So we want to help as
much as we possibly

00:19:50.930 --> 00:19:54.320
can, save as many lives,
reduce as much suffering.

00:19:54.320 --> 00:19:56.120
So in our campaigns
and in our work,

00:19:56.120 --> 00:19:58.610
we look at the number of
animals affected, the duration

00:19:58.610 --> 00:20:01.070
of suffering, the
degree of suffering,

00:20:01.070 --> 00:20:04.550
and where there are
viable alternatives.

00:20:04.550 --> 00:20:08.410
And while we push forward
for a vegan world--

00:20:08.410 --> 00:20:10.290
and I'll talk more about that--

00:20:10.290 --> 00:20:12.290
we also believe that it's
our ethical obligation

00:20:12.290 --> 00:20:14.450
to prevent as much
suffering as we can

00:20:14.450 --> 00:20:16.760
for the animals
unfortunate enough to be

00:20:16.760 --> 00:20:19.620
born now and in the future.

00:20:19.620 --> 00:20:21.920
So part of that
includes changing laws

00:20:21.920 --> 00:20:25.490
and pushing for policy
changes, as I mentioned before.

00:20:25.490 --> 00:20:27.350
And we look at the
internationally accepted

00:20:27.350 --> 00:20:29.690
five freedoms as a
base for that work,

00:20:29.690 --> 00:20:31.610
and that's freedom
from hunger and thirst,

00:20:31.610 --> 00:20:35.309
freedom from discomfort, freedom
from pain, injury, and disease,

00:20:35.309 --> 00:20:37.100
freedom from fear and
distress, and freedom

00:20:37.100 --> 00:20:41.810
to express normal behavior.

00:20:41.810 --> 00:20:45.290
Simple terms, but vast impact.

00:20:45.290 --> 00:20:48.050
That means addressing
the intensive confinement

00:20:48.050 --> 00:20:50.750
of animals, like those mother
pigs that I just told you

00:20:50.750 --> 00:20:54.950
about, and ending
gestation crates,

00:20:54.950 --> 00:20:58.400
ending the confinement of egg
laying hens in battery cages--

00:20:58.400 --> 00:21:02.720
file cabinet-sized cages,
where five to seven birds are

00:21:02.720 --> 00:21:05.304
kept for their entire lives,
unable to spread their wings,

00:21:05.304 --> 00:21:06.970
walk, perch, roost,
[INAUDIBLE],, bathe,

00:21:06.970 --> 00:21:09.260
or engage in the most
basic natural behaviors.

00:21:09.260 --> 00:21:12.800
It means ending the confinement
of baby calves inside

00:21:12.800 --> 00:21:15.620
of veal crates.

00:21:15.620 --> 00:21:17.180
And we're having success.

00:21:17.180 --> 00:21:19.130
We have pushed many of
the largest players--

00:21:19.130 --> 00:21:22.520
everyone from Wal-Mart to
McDonald's-- to address these

00:21:22.520 --> 00:21:23.160
abuses.

00:21:23.160 --> 00:21:26.550
Now, this doesn't mean that
these animals live happy lives.

00:21:26.550 --> 00:21:28.340
And in fact, many
of these commitments

00:21:28.340 --> 00:21:31.040
have phase-in periods
of 10 years or more,

00:21:31.040 --> 00:21:33.470
but it is moving
the ball forward,

00:21:33.470 --> 00:21:35.870
showing that these
animals' lives matter,

00:21:35.870 --> 00:21:39.950
and that the treatment of them
during those lives matter.

00:21:39.950 --> 00:21:43.880
Our main focus right now
is on birds used for meat.

00:21:43.880 --> 00:21:48.170
Broiler chickens-- literally
named after the cooking method.

00:21:48.170 --> 00:21:50.240
These are birds that
have been bred to be

00:21:50.240 --> 00:21:51.770
almost Frankenstein animals.

00:21:51.770 --> 00:21:53.900
Bred to grow so
large and so fast

00:21:53.900 --> 00:21:56.420
that they're killed when
they're 45 days old--

00:21:56.420 --> 00:21:58.170
babies.

00:21:58.170 --> 00:22:01.950
And they suffer under the
weight of their own bodies.

00:22:01.950 --> 00:22:04.590
There's not a single federal
law that provides protection

00:22:04.590 --> 00:22:07.560
to animals during their
lives on factory farms,

00:22:07.560 --> 00:22:09.390
and the only
federal laws that do

00:22:09.390 --> 00:22:13.020
exist are related to the
final moments of the animals

00:22:13.020 --> 00:22:14.370
lives-- transport and slaughter.

00:22:14.370 --> 00:22:19.020
And of that, they exempt
birds, which make up

00:22:19.020 --> 00:22:21.540
the 95% of farmed animals.

00:22:21.540 --> 00:22:24.540
So the way in which chickens are
killed in this country, that's

00:22:24.540 --> 00:22:27.160
considered standard and
legal, would be illegal

00:22:27.160 --> 00:22:31.330
if it was a dog or a
cat, and a cow or a pig.

00:22:31.330 --> 00:22:33.210
So we're working to
change that as well.

00:22:33.210 --> 00:22:36.814
These birds are dumped out of
crates, snapped into shackles.

00:22:36.814 --> 00:22:39.230
They have their throats slit
while they're fully conscious

00:22:39.230 --> 00:22:42.327
often times, and many of them
go into scalding tanks of water

00:22:42.327 --> 00:22:43.410
while they're still alive.

00:22:43.410 --> 00:22:45.880
The USDA says at least
a million birds a year,

00:22:45.880 --> 00:22:50.510
but we know that the number
is, in fact, much higher.

00:22:50.510 --> 00:22:53.660
So we're working to reduce
the suffering of these birds

00:22:53.660 --> 00:22:55.970
through pressuring
companies to change

00:22:55.970 --> 00:22:58.400
the genetics of these birds,
give them natural light,

00:22:58.400 --> 00:22:59.900
enrichments that
they have something

00:22:59.900 --> 00:23:02.300
to do during their
miserable existence,

00:23:02.300 --> 00:23:05.630
reduce stocking density, and
change slaughter practices.

00:23:05.630 --> 00:23:07.550
And in just the last
year, we've been

00:23:07.550 --> 00:23:10.520
able to pressure over
100 of the largest food

00:23:10.520 --> 00:23:13.040
companies in the world
to make these changes,

00:23:13.040 --> 00:23:17.180
affecting over 1 billion birds.

00:23:17.180 --> 00:23:20.040
But we're also addressing
this on the political front.

00:23:20.040 --> 00:23:24.400
Now, there is no clear
roadmap right now

00:23:24.400 --> 00:23:27.050
for federal legislation
that would protect animals.

00:23:27.050 --> 00:23:28.954
So we have to look
at the state level.

00:23:28.954 --> 00:23:31.120
Half of the states don't
even have ballot initiative

00:23:31.120 --> 00:23:34.390
processes, but California does.

00:23:34.390 --> 00:23:37.810
And we are part of a coalition
that is launching right now.

00:23:37.810 --> 00:23:42.010
An initiative that would end
the cage confinement of birds,

00:23:42.010 --> 00:23:44.860
cows, and pigs in
California, but also

00:23:44.860 --> 00:23:48.070
the sale of meat and
eggs from birds that

00:23:48.070 --> 00:23:49.330
are kept in these enclosures.

00:23:49.330 --> 00:23:51.040
So if you're
interested, please go

00:23:51.040 --> 00:23:56.970
to preventcrueltyca.com to get
involved in that initiative.

00:23:56.970 --> 00:23:59.580
These efforts are
having a real impact,

00:23:59.580 --> 00:24:06.130
as I said-- impacting over
1 billion animals year-wide.

00:24:06.130 --> 00:24:11.870
$1 to MFA helps 111 animals--

00:24:11.870 --> 00:24:15.290
reduce the suffering of these
animals through policy changes,

00:24:15.290 --> 00:24:19.170
and spares one animal from ever
being born into factory farms.

00:24:19.170 --> 00:24:21.290
This is our view of
effective altruism.

00:24:21.290 --> 00:24:24.540
How can we stretch the dollar
to impact the most animals.

00:24:24.540 --> 00:24:26.660
Though again, we won't
meet these animals,

00:24:26.660 --> 00:24:29.390
but prevention goes so
far in helping them.

00:24:29.390 --> 00:24:32.630
We also believe that
where an animal is born,

00:24:32.630 --> 00:24:35.630
or where an animal
hatches, shouldn't dictate

00:24:35.630 --> 00:24:37.482
whether they live
lives of suffering

00:24:37.482 --> 00:24:38.690
or whether they have respect.

00:24:38.690 --> 00:24:41.930
We believe that a pig in
China and a pig in the US

00:24:41.930 --> 00:24:44.120
deserve the same sort
of consideration.

00:24:44.120 --> 00:24:47.660
That a chicken in Canada
or a chicken in Mexico

00:24:47.660 --> 00:24:51.050
deserve the same consideration.

00:24:51.050 --> 00:24:53.760
And while we make progress
here in the United States,

00:24:53.760 --> 00:24:56.610
the truth is, is that only
about 2% of farmed animals

00:24:56.610 --> 00:24:57.900
are in the US.

00:24:57.900 --> 00:25:01.710
The other 98% are
on a global level--

00:25:01.710 --> 00:25:03.870
about half of this in China.

00:25:03.870 --> 00:25:07.380
And this includes
fish that are farmed.

00:25:07.380 --> 00:25:11.400
And unfortunately, we are seeing
an increase in meat consumption

00:25:11.400 --> 00:25:13.600
and production on
a global scale.

00:25:13.600 --> 00:25:18.150
In fact, it is estimated that
by 2050, global meat production

00:25:18.150 --> 00:25:19.290
will double.

00:25:19.290 --> 00:25:21.240
So we need to come up
with innovative ways

00:25:21.240 --> 00:25:25.905
to address this, which I'll
talk about a bit later.

00:25:25.905 --> 00:25:27.280
One way in which
we're doing this

00:25:27.280 --> 00:25:31.060
is by launching offices and
campaigns around the globe.

00:25:31.060 --> 00:25:35.410
We now have a presence in six
countries together representing

00:25:35.410 --> 00:25:38.290
over half of the global
human population.

00:25:38.290 --> 00:25:40.000
These are slides
of investigations

00:25:40.000 --> 00:25:45.760
that we carried out in Mexico
at over a dozen government owned

00:25:45.760 --> 00:25:47.290
slaughterhouses.

00:25:47.290 --> 00:25:51.340
And we documented pigs
having their hearts cut

00:25:51.340 --> 00:25:55.340
open while still alive,
being electrically shocked,

00:25:55.340 --> 00:26:01.270
hammers being used to kill
adult cows and steers.

00:26:01.270 --> 00:26:03.760
Now, we used this
investigation to push

00:26:03.760 --> 00:26:05.870
for federal legislation.

00:26:05.870 --> 00:26:10.330
And I'm excited to say that it
is moving through the Mexico

00:26:10.330 --> 00:26:12.480
legislature as we speak.

00:26:12.480 --> 00:26:15.370
In just the last week, it passed
the equivalent of the House

00:26:15.370 --> 00:26:19.240
in Mexico, and it is now
going before the Senate.

00:26:19.240 --> 00:26:21.070
And we are optimistic
that it will pass

00:26:21.070 --> 00:26:23.440
and be signed by the president.

00:26:23.440 --> 00:26:25.450
And what this piece
of legislation does

00:26:25.450 --> 00:26:28.802
