and other forms of oil.

00:30:26.740 --> 00:30:29.800
If we look at what's happening
right here in Silicon

00:30:29.800 --> 00:30:32.440
Valley, how
innovation is changing

00:30:32.440 --> 00:30:36.010
the way in which people
travel, where they stay,

00:30:36.010 --> 00:30:37.900
how they gather
information, we can

00:30:37.900 --> 00:30:42.620
see that simple ideas
can change the world.

00:30:42.620 --> 00:30:44.500
And I believe that
animal agriculture

00:30:44.500 --> 00:30:48.250
is ripe for this
type of disruption.

00:30:48.250 --> 00:30:52.580
Not only is it inhumane, but
it is completely inefficient.

00:30:52.580 --> 00:30:55.480
We think about the amount
of grain and energy

00:30:55.480 --> 00:30:58.270
that has to be used to produce
that grain to funnel it

00:30:58.270 --> 00:31:01.150
through animals to get
a small amount of meat,

00:31:01.150 --> 00:31:02.710
it doesn't make sense.

00:31:02.710 --> 00:31:03.790
It's not sustainable.

00:31:03.790 --> 00:31:08.560
As we race towards a global
population of 9.7 billion

00:31:08.560 --> 00:31:15.570
by 2050, we simply can't
grow and feed enough animals

00:31:15.570 --> 00:31:18.010
to feed the growing population.

00:31:18.010 --> 00:31:19.940
Now, Richard Branson
recently said,

00:31:19.940 --> 00:31:22.210
"I believe that
in 30 years or so,

00:31:22.210 --> 00:31:25.180
we will no longer need
to kill any animals,

00:31:25.180 --> 00:31:28.630
and that all meat will either
be clean or plant-based,

00:31:28.630 --> 00:31:32.830
taste the same, and also be
much healthier for everyone."

00:31:32.830 --> 00:31:35.500
And Mr. Branson
is a new investor

00:31:35.500 --> 00:31:40.720
in Memphis Meats, a company that
was founded by Uma Valeti, who

00:31:40.720 --> 00:31:42.230
is a cardiologist.

00:31:42.230 --> 00:31:45.070
He was saving
lives in hospitals,

00:31:45.070 --> 00:31:48.520
and he realized that in
the medical profession,

00:31:48.520 --> 00:31:50.470
they were growing
tissues for quite

00:31:50.470 --> 00:31:52.130
some time for medical purposes.

00:31:52.130 --> 00:31:56.380
And he thought, can't we use
this same technology to raise

00:31:56.380 --> 00:31:58.270
meat-- meat without the murder--

00:31:58.270 --> 00:32:00.880
something that Google
has been at the forefront

00:32:00.880 --> 00:32:03.310
of, with Sergey Brin,
of course, funding

00:32:03.310 --> 00:32:07.630
the first lab-grown burger
from Mark Post just a number

00:32:07.630 --> 00:32:09.070
of years ago.

00:32:09.070 --> 00:32:11.560
Now, Uma started
Memphis Meats, and it's

00:32:11.560 --> 00:32:13.750
called Memphis Meats because
one of his co-founders

00:32:13.750 --> 00:32:17.680
is from Memphis and actually
owns and runs barbecue meat

00:32:17.680 --> 00:32:20.740
restaurants there and would
like to have clean meat

00:32:20.740 --> 00:32:24.340
to be able to serve in
his restaurants one day.

00:32:24.340 --> 00:32:27.010
Now Uma and his
team have created

00:32:27.010 --> 00:32:29.890
the world's first clean
meatball, but also

00:32:29.890 --> 00:32:34.480
the world's first clean
chicken and duck products just

00:32:34.480 --> 00:32:37.210
in the last few years.

00:32:37.210 --> 00:32:40.750
And it is called clean meat
as a nod to clean energy.

00:32:40.750 --> 00:32:45.730
It takes about 50% less
energy to produce clean meat,

00:32:45.730 --> 00:32:49.330
and produces about 90% less
greenhouse gas emissions,

00:32:49.330 --> 00:32:56.480
requires 90% less land
and water as well.

00:32:56.480 --> 00:33:00.510
But it's also called clean meat
because it is literally cleaner

00:33:00.510 --> 00:33:05.010
to produce in bioreactors,
much the same way

00:33:05.010 --> 00:33:06.190
that beer is produced.

00:33:06.190 --> 00:33:09.930
So you're not going to find
the same levels of bacteria

00:33:09.930 --> 00:33:10.710
contamination--

00:33:10.710 --> 00:33:14.010
E. Coli, salmonella,
campylobacter, et cetera.

00:33:14.010 --> 00:33:18.990
This chart shows Memphis
Meats' antibiotic and bacteria

00:33:18.990 --> 00:33:22.200
levels compared to conventional
and organic levels.

00:33:22.200 --> 00:33:24.970
It's pretty clear.

00:33:24.970 --> 00:33:27.370
"The Guardian's"
headline sums it up.

00:33:27.370 --> 00:33:31.150
They said, "Lab-grown food--
the goal is to remove the animal

00:33:31.150 --> 00:33:32.890
from meat production."

00:33:32.890 --> 00:33:36.190
And Uma considers this
the second domestication.

00:33:36.190 --> 00:33:37.922
The first domestication--

00:33:37.922 --> 00:33:39.880
10,000 years ago, the
Neolithic period, which I

00:33:39.880 --> 00:33:41.170
mentioned before.

00:33:41.170 --> 00:33:44.560
This being cellular
agriculture, a reflection

00:33:44.560 --> 00:33:46.720
of not only our
ethical evolution,

00:33:46.720 --> 00:33:50.530
but also our increased
understanding of science

00:33:50.530 --> 00:33:53.200
and being able to cut
animals out of the equation

00:33:53.200 --> 00:33:55.450
and get right to the
heart of the matter.

00:33:58.030 --> 00:34:01.210
I believe so firmly
in the ability

00:34:01.210 --> 00:34:04.660
for clean meat and plant-based
meat to revolutionize the way

00:34:04.660 --> 00:34:07.000
that we eat, and in the
process, eliminate factory

00:34:07.000 --> 00:34:09.610
farming that I helped start
The Good Food Institute,

00:34:09.610 --> 00:34:11.770
which you heard a
little bit about before.

00:34:11.770 --> 00:34:13.600
This is a nonprofit
that supports

00:34:13.600 --> 00:34:15.760
the entire plant-based
and clean meat

00:34:15.760 --> 00:34:20.710
sector by supporting scientists
and technology, innovation,

00:34:20.710 --> 00:34:23.409
and policy work, making sure
that when clean meat comes

00:34:23.409 --> 00:34:27.429
to market, that it won't face
any legal hurdles and community

00:34:27.429 --> 00:34:28.929
engagement.

00:34:28.929 --> 00:34:31.389
Also, starting new crop
capital-- putting our money

00:34:31.389 --> 00:34:32.710
where our mouth is.

00:34:32.710 --> 00:34:36.250
Doing angel seed investing
in companies that are high

00:34:36.250 --> 00:34:39.040
risk, but have the potential
to change the world.

00:34:39.040 --> 00:34:42.940
Investing in companies, like
Memphis Meats, Beyond Meat,

00:34:42.940 --> 00:34:45.370
Lyrical Foods, Good Catch--

00:34:45.370 --> 00:34:48.400
companies that are
seeking to create vegan,

00:34:48.400 --> 00:34:50.860
plant-based
alternatives to fish.

00:34:50.860 --> 00:34:56.250
We are racing towards having
a fishless ocean by 2048,

00:34:56.250 --> 00:35:00.320
with most of the wild
stocks in severe decline.

00:35:00.320 --> 00:35:03.190
This is a moral and
ethical issue as much

00:35:03.190 --> 00:35:08.480
as it is a conservation and
environmental issue as well.

00:35:08.480 --> 00:35:13.160
And we have good company
with these investments

00:35:13.160 --> 00:35:17.200
that we are making-- perhaps
unusual, you might think.

00:35:17.200 --> 00:35:20.030
The Tyson Foods CEO says
that the future of food

00:35:20.030 --> 00:35:23.780
might be meatless, reflecting
a 5% investment that they

00:35:23.780 --> 00:35:27.050
recently did in Beyond Meat.

00:35:27.050 --> 00:35:29.810
Cargill, one of the largest
meat companies in the US,

00:35:29.810 --> 00:35:34.610
recently did an investment
alongside Bill Gates and others

00:35:34.610 --> 00:35:36.840
in Memphis Meats itself.

00:35:36.840 --> 00:35:39.890
This is something
that I welcome.

00:35:39.890 --> 00:35:45.100
Just as the car changed
the transportation sector,

00:35:45.100 --> 00:35:46.850
we believe that
plant-based and clean meat

00:35:46.850 --> 00:35:49.320
can change the protein sector.

00:35:49.320 --> 00:35:52.760
So we want companies in the
protein sector to embrace this,

00:35:52.760 --> 00:35:54.620
make this part of
their business plan.

00:35:54.620 --> 00:36:00.890
And we are seeing that happen
at an alarmingly great rate.

00:36:00.890 --> 00:36:03.890
Now, I want to talk a little
bit about change over time.

00:36:03.890 --> 00:36:06.410
Just a few years ago,
people would say clean meat,

00:36:06.410 --> 00:36:09.260
ending factory farming,
this is crazy talk,

00:36:09.260 --> 00:36:10.970
it's never going to happen.

00:36:10.970 --> 00:36:14.510
This is too deeply ingrained
in our culture and our beliefs,

00:36:14.510 --> 00:36:17.240
but a little bit of
historical perspective I think

00:36:17.240 --> 00:36:19.880
can show how quickly
things can change.

00:36:19.880 --> 00:36:23.060
Dr. King once said that the
arc of the moral universe

00:36:23.060 --> 00:36:26.400
is long, but bends
towards justice.

00:36:26.400 --> 00:36:28.340
And this is true.

00:36:28.340 --> 00:36:31.430
Our history books are filled
with examples of this.

00:36:31.430 --> 00:36:33.050
But that arc of
the moral universe,

00:36:33.050 --> 00:36:35.390
it doesn't bend on its own.

00:36:35.390 --> 00:36:37.550
It doesn't bend because
of the weight of time.

00:36:37.550 --> 00:36:41.570
It bends because thoughtful,
committed, concerned people

00:36:41.570 --> 00:36:44.390
step up to the plate
and they take action,

00:36:44.390 --> 00:36:46.820
whether that's protesting,
speaking out, founding

00:36:46.820 --> 00:36:50.120
organizations, supporting
organizations, or being

00:36:50.120 --> 00:36:53.150
innovators in the space.

00:36:53.150 --> 00:36:57.920
Just 150 years ago, we ended
slavery in this country--

00:36:57.920 --> 00:37:00.170
owning another human,
considering them

00:37:00.170 --> 00:37:02.870
as chattel and property.

00:37:02.870 --> 00:37:07.570
97 years ago, women were
finally given the right to vote.

00:37:07.570 --> 00:37:09.460
There were impassioned
debates in Congress

00:37:09.460 --> 00:37:12.070
about women being too
irrational of creatures

00:37:12.070 --> 00:37:14.290
to be able to vote.

00:37:14.290 --> 00:37:19.270
Funny considering
the situation today.

00:37:19.270 --> 00:37:22.840
Just 53 years ago,
we ended segregation

00:37:22.840 --> 00:37:27.450
in this country-- something
that was fought tooth and nail.

00:37:27.450 --> 00:37:30.900
Just 50 years ago, in
Loving versus Virginia,

00:37:30.900 --> 00:37:34.200
interracial marriage was
legalized across the United

00:37:34.200 --> 00:37:36.240
States, striking
down certain state

00:37:36.240 --> 00:37:37.560
laws that made it a crime.

00:37:37.560 --> 00:37:40.290
People were arrested
in their own homes

00:37:40.290 --> 00:37:42.970
because of who they loved.

00:37:42.970 --> 00:37:46.540
And just two years ago,
my love, and others

00:37:46.540 --> 00:37:49.930
in the LGBT community, finally
recognized in our country

00:37:49.930 --> 00:37:55.830
on a national level with
the Supreme Court decision.

00:37:55.830 --> 00:37:58.510
Now, when I grew up
on a farm in Ohio,

00:37:58.510 --> 00:38:02.610
I was called a faggot before I
knew what the word even meant.

00:38:02.610 --> 00:38:04.770
And I was taught
and told by society

00:38:04.770 --> 00:38:07.990
that my love wasn't equal, and
I can tell you, at a young age,

00:38:07.990 --> 00:38:11.220
there were many times when
I thought that I would never

00:38:11.220 --> 00:38:12.390
be able to get married.

00:38:12.390 --> 00:38:14.910
That society would never
progress to a point

00:38:14.910 --> 00:38:16.170
where that would happen.

00:38:16.170 --> 00:38:18.830
And I can only imagine,
when people like Rosa Parks

00:38:18.830 --> 00:38:21.480
are being dragged off of
buses, that they probably

00:38:21.480 --> 00:38:24.150
didn't know when
or if they would

00:38:24.150 --> 00:38:26.830
see those changes
in their lifetime,

00:38:26.830 --> 00:38:28.530
but they pushed forward.

00:38:28.530 --> 00:38:32.650
And society is
better because of it.

00:38:32.650 --> 00:38:36.640
Nelson Mandela who was a
political prisoner, released,

00:38:36.640 --> 00:38:39.880
and became the president
of South Africa, once

00:38:39.880 --> 00:38:44.540
said, "It always seems
impossible until it's done."

00:38:44.540 --> 00:38:45.804
And then it seems inevitable.

00:38:45.804 --> 00:38:47.470
And again, we can
look at history books,

00:38:47.470 --> 00:38:50.157
and we can say, of
course, slavery would end.

00:38:50.157 --> 00:38:52.240
Of course, women would be
given the right to vote.

00:38:52.240 --> 00:38:55.270
Of course,
segregation would end.

00:38:55.270 --> 00:38:58.160
But again, it didn't
happen on its own.

00:38:58.160 --> 00:39:00.880
Now Peter Singer, author
of "Animal Liberation"

00:39:00.880 --> 00:39:04.720
and many other wonderful books,
once said it's easy for us

00:39:04.720 --> 00:39:08.350
to criticize the prejudices
of our grandfathers

00:39:08.350 --> 00:39:12.440
from which they freed
themselves from their fathers,

00:39:12.440 --> 00:39:15.610
but it is more difficult for
us to dispassionately search

00:39:15.610 --> 00:39:19.950
for prejudices in
our own beliefs.

00:39:19.950 --> 00:39:22.440
And I believe that
animal protection,

00:39:22.440 --> 00:39:26.130
animal rights is a
social justice issue.

00:39:26.130 --> 00:39:29.100
And if we look at the number of
individuals that are suffering

00:39:29.100 --> 00:39:31.330
and the degree to which
they are suffering,

00:39:31.330 --> 00:39:35.500
I think it is one of the most
pressing social justice issues.

00:39:35.500 --> 00:39:40.890
And it is different from other
past movements in the sense

00:39:40.890 --> 00:39:43.650
that those who are being
oppressed and marginalized,

00:39:43.650 --> 00:39:46.020
they can't speak up
on their own behalf.

00:39:46.020 --> 00:39:49.000
They can't stand up here
and share their stories.

00:39:49.000 --> 00:39:51.810
They can't lobby
Congress to pass laws.

00:39:51.810 --> 00:39:54.030
They can't organize boycotts.

00:39:54.030 --> 00:39:56.190
They rely on each
and every one of us

00:39:56.190 --> 00:40:00.120
to do that on their behalf in
our own unique and meaningful

00:40:00.120 --> 00:40:01.980
ways.

00:40:01.980 --> 00:40:04.840
But if we stop for a moment
and we look and we listen,

00:40:04.840 --> 00:40:07.730
we see that these
animals are protesting.

00:40:07.730 --> 00:40:09.040
They are struggling.

00:40:09.040 --> 00:40:11.800
They are trying to save their
own lives and often times,

00:40:11.800 --> 00:40:14.140
the lives of others
that they care about.

00:40:14.140 --> 00:40:18.580
This is an image from China
of a brave pig who jumped out

00:40:18.580 --> 00:40:20.710
of the top of a
moving transport truck

00:40:20.710 --> 00:40:23.920
on her way to slaughter
to save her own life.

00:40:23.920 --> 00:40:26.510
And it seems like every few
weeks, every few months,

00:40:26.510 --> 00:40:29.470
we see stories in
the paper of animals

00:40:29.470 --> 00:40:32.350
who jumped over fences to save
themselves from slaughter.

00:40:32.350 --> 00:40:35.826
And when that happens, everyone
rallies behind those animals.

00:40:35.826 --> 00:40:36.950
They want them to be saved.

00:40:36.950 --> 00:40:39.900
They want them to
go to sanctuaries.

00:40:39.900 --> 00:40:41.470
Each animal deserves that.

00:40:44.240 --> 00:40:48.080
I just want to share this story,
which I'm sure many of you

00:40:48.080 --> 00:40:49.430
have heard before.

00:40:49.430 --> 00:40:53.630
A little boy is at the
beach with his grandfather,

00:40:53.630 --> 00:40:55.460
and there are hundreds
of starfish that

00:40:55.460 --> 00:40:57.770
have washed up along the shore.

00:40:57.770 --> 00:41:00.920
And the little boy is tossing
them back into the water, one

00:41:00.920 --> 00:41:01.880
after the next.

00:41:01.880 --> 00:41:06.860
And his grandfather looks at him
and says, what are you doing?

00:41:06.860 --> 00:41:09.050
There are maybe thousands
of starfish here.

00:41:09.050 --> 00:41:11.090
You can't possibly
save them all.

00:41:11.090 --> 00:41:14.180
And the little boy smiles
back at his grandfather.

00:41:14.180 --> 00:41:15.110
He reaches down.

00:41:15.110 --> 00:41:17.615
He picks up another starfish
and gently tosses him back

00:41:17.615 --> 00:41:18.240
into the water.

00:41:18.240 --> 00:41:21.620
And he said, it
matters to this one.

00:41:21.620 --> 00:41:23.949
And he reaches back down,
picks up another one,

00:41:23.949 --> 00:41:25.490
puts him back in
the water, and says,

00:41:25.490 --> 00:41:28.060
and it matters to this one.

00:41:28.060 --> 00:41:32.880
And to me, this story
really illustrates the power

00:41:32.880 --> 00:41:36.300
that we have to save
lives, to prevent cruelty,

00:41:36.300 --> 00:41:38.040
to improve the world.

00:41:38.040 --> 00:41:44.220
And how any act of kindness is
never wasted in little choices

00:41:44.220 --> 00:41:45.330
that we make.

00:41:45.330 --> 00:41:47.520
Maybe it's the food
choices that we

00:41:47.520 --> 00:41:51.600
make that can have profound
consequences for animals.

00:41:51.600 --> 00:41:55.844
It can be the difference
between life or death.

00:41:55.844 --> 00:41:58.260
So I leave you with this quote
from Harriet Beecher Stowe.

00:41:58.260 --> 00:41:59.370
She said, it's a
matter of taking

00:41:59.370 --> 00:42:01.260
the side of the weak
against the strong--

00:42:01.260 --> 00:42:03.780
something the best
people have always done.

00:42:03.780 --> 00:42:06.390
And it is difficult to
imagine a group of individuals

00:42:06.390 --> 00:42:11.310
who are weaker and more
vulnerable than animals.

00:42:11.310 --> 00:42:14.010
And within that
group, farmed animals.

00:42:14.010 --> 00:42:16.830
So thank you for being
here and for being

00:42:16.830 --> 00:42:20.551
on the side of the
weak and vulnerable.

00:42:20.551 --> 00:42:23.960
[APPLAUSE]

00:42:29.330 --> 00:42:32.220
Do we have time for questions?

00:42:32.220 --> 00:42:35.780
AUDIENCE: So, we see things
like "Happy Feet," where

00:42:35.780 --> 00:42:39.290
an animal's communicating
with the world, and we all

00:42:39.290 --> 00:42:41.600
[INAUDIBLE],, but I feel
like they communicate

00:42:41.600 --> 00:42:43.360
with us all of the time.

00:42:43.360 --> 00:42:47.690
So what, for instance, from
connecting our emotions

00:42:47.690 --> 00:42:50.730
that we have for our pets
with all of the other animals

00:42:50.730 --> 00:42:52.032
that we see in the world?

00:42:52.032 --> 00:42:53.840
I know some of it is
a bit brainwashing,

00:42:53.840 --> 00:42:56.094
but what inherently
is preventing us

00:42:56.094 --> 00:42:57.260
from making that connection?

00:42:57.260 --> 00:42:58.100
I don't understand.

00:42:58.100 --> 00:43:00.980
NATHAN RUNKLE: Yeah, I mean,
on this sort of brainwashing,

00:43:00.980 --> 00:43:04.170
Melanie Joy has written a book--

00:43:04.170 --> 00:43:05.720
well, she's written three books.

00:43:05.720 --> 00:43:11.720
One is called "Why We Eat Pigs,
Wear Cows, and Love Dogs."

00:43:11.720 --> 00:43:13.460
And she talks about
carnism, which

00:43:13.460 --> 00:43:19.010
is this invisible belief that
allows us to eat some animals,

00:43:19.010 --> 00:43:19.760
but not others.

00:43:19.760 --> 00:43:22.550
And the truth is that we
don't eat most animal species.

00:43:22.550 --> 00:43:26.100
It's actually a very small
number of cows, pigs, chickens,

00:43:26.100 --> 00:43:28.400
turkeys, ducks.

00:43:28.400 --> 00:43:34.400
And it really is a belief system
that allows us to do that.

00:43:34.400 --> 00:43:40.970
I think that part of it is that
it is social conditioning that

00:43:40.970 --> 00:43:43.814
is reinforced all
the time, and we

00:43:43.814 --> 00:43:45.980
don't know that we're being
conditioned in that way.

00:43:45.980 --> 00:43:47.900
It starts at a very
young age, especially

00:43:47.900 --> 00:43:52.470
in the United States
and Western cultures.

00:43:52.470 --> 00:43:55.460
So I think part of it is
that these animals are

00:43:55.460 --> 00:43:57.500
sort of ghosts in our
industrial machine.

00:43:57.500 --> 00:43:58.670
People don't see them.

00:43:58.670 --> 00:44:02.330
You go to the grocery store and
you pick up a package of meat

00:44:02.330 --> 00:44:05.405
and it doesn't resemble an
animal, and we call it beef

00:44:05.405 --> 00:44:07.340
or we call it pork.

00:44:07.340 --> 00:44:08.810
So I think that's
a big part of it,

00:44:08.810 --> 00:44:12.739
is people are able to have
willful ignorance that they

00:44:12.739 --> 00:44:14.780
don't want to know about
something so they're not

00:44:14.780 --> 00:44:16.300
going to.

00:44:16.300 --> 00:44:20.330
And I think that that is
one of the driving forces.

00:44:20.330 --> 00:44:22.467
And there's also just
so many social norms.

00:44:22.467 --> 00:44:24.050
People don't even
realize that they're

00:44:24.050 --> 00:44:26.820
making a choice so much.

00:44:26.820 --> 00:44:29.840
So I think that that's one
of the most important things,

00:44:29.840 --> 00:44:33.380
is as plant-based eating,
as vegan eating becomes more

00:44:33.380 --> 00:44:36.410
mainstream, and people
see others doing it

00:44:36.410 --> 00:44:40.829
and it becomes a default
option, that will go a long way.

00:44:40.829 --> 00:44:42.870
But part of what we want
to do with The Good Food

00:44:42.870 --> 00:44:46.840
Institute, for example, is the
three main factors for people

00:44:46.840 --> 00:44:50.150
in their eating is
convenience, taste, and price.

00:44:50.150 --> 00:44:53.390
So we want to make the
compassionate choice

00:44:53.390 --> 00:44:55.520
the default choice
so that maybe we

00:44:55.520 --> 00:44:57.710
don't need to win over
everyone's hearts and minds,

00:44:57.710 --> 00:44:59.640
but they can simply
go to a store

00:44:59.640 --> 00:45:00.980
and that's what they're eating.

00:45:00.980 --> 00:45:04.550
And maybe it's clean
meat and it's real meat,

00:45:04.550 --> 00:45:07.050
it's just produced
in a different way.

00:45:07.050 --> 00:45:09.600
So I think that that's
really exciting,

00:45:09.600 --> 00:45:11.390
and I think, honestly,
the way that we're

00:45:11.390 --> 00:45:14.660
going to drive down consumption
as quickly as we can.

00:45:14.660 --> 00:45:15.430
Yeah, thank you.

00:45:16.091 --> 00:45:18.340
AUDIENCE: Do you have a list,
or some sort of resource

00:45:18.340 --> 00:45:22.470
where you have
meat producers that

00:45:22.470 --> 00:45:25.381
do use humane processes today?

00:45:25.381 --> 00:45:26.380
NATHAN RUNKLE: We don't.

00:45:26.380 --> 00:45:28.430
So Mercy for Animals
is never going

00:45:28.430 --> 00:45:31.490
to endorse a meat company.

00:45:31.490 --> 00:45:34.040
Like I said, we think
the only compassionate

00:45:34.040 --> 00:45:35.280
choice is a plant-based diet.

00:45:35.280 --> 00:45:38.870
But as I said before,
we believe that it's

00:45:38.870 --> 00:45:42.160
our obligation to prevent as
much suffering as possible.

00:45:42.160 --> 00:45:44.480
So that means pushing companies
away from this process.

00:45:44.480 --> 00:45:45.980
So we don't have a
list of companies

00:45:45.980 --> 00:45:48.410
that we endorse,
and we never will.

00:45:48.410 --> 00:45:52.900
But there are different
labeling programs that are used.

00:45:52.900 --> 00:45:57.350
And people who aren't yet ready
to go completely plant based,

00:45:57.350 --> 00:45:59.720
I think the best thing you
can do is eat less meat.

00:45:59.720 --> 00:46:01.580
I think a lot of
people will think,

00:46:01.580 --> 00:46:05.000
hey I don't identify as vegan,
I don't think I ever could.

00:46:05.000 --> 00:46:06.170
That's OK.

00:46:06.170 --> 00:46:07.760
If everyone ate
meatless on Monday,

00:46:07.760 --> 00:46:10.440
a billion fewer animals
would be killed.

00:46:10.440 --> 00:46:13.850
And if people start moving in
that direction, it's better.

00:46:13.850 --> 00:46:15.802
So people, especially
as they are starting,

00:46:15.802 --> 00:46:17.510
shouldn't view this
as an all or nothing.

00:46:17.510 --> 00:46:20.600
Because when people do that,
oftentimes they do nothing.

00:46:20.600 --> 00:46:25.400
And we need people to make
choices that help animals.

00:46:25.400 --> 00:46:29.180
But the labels that are thrown
around can be so deceptive.

00:46:29.180 --> 00:46:32.000
For example, there's the
American Humane Association,

00:46:32.000 --> 00:46:37.390
which certifies Foster Farms
chicken and Butterball.

00:46:37.390 --> 00:46:40.160
It's essentially a completely
meaningless program.

00:46:40.160 --> 00:46:43.040
It really just rubber stamps
what the industry is already

00:46:43.040 --> 00:46:44.060
doing.

00:46:44.060 --> 00:46:46.370
And we've seen this
with the egg industry.

00:46:46.370 --> 00:46:49.560
A few years ago, they started
Animal Care Certified labeling,

00:46:49.560 --> 00:46:53.840
which meant they took one bird
out of each cage, that's it.

00:46:53.840 --> 00:46:55.790
The Better Business
Bureau got involved,

00:46:55.790 --> 00:46:57.300
they said this is misleading.

00:46:57.300 --> 00:47:00.230
So they change it to United
Egg Producer certified.

00:47:00.230 --> 00:47:02.680
So the industry knows that
people care about this.

00:47:02.680 --> 00:47:05.930
There's a lot of humane
washing that's happening.

00:47:05.930 --> 00:47:08.379
So if you are going to
choose to eat these products,

00:47:08.379 --> 00:47:09.920
I think at the very
least, you should

00:47:09.920 --> 00:47:11.450
know what the labels mean.

00:47:11.450 --> 00:47:13.880
Because they can vary so much.

00:47:13.880 --> 00:47:17.070
And you just need to do
your own research on that.

00:47:17.070 --> 00:47:20.840
I know that there is Farm
Forward, an organization that

00:47:20.840 --> 00:47:25.460
works on animal welfare
issues for food,

00:47:25.460 --> 00:47:28.370
has a website called
buyingpoultry.com,

00:47:28.370 --> 00:47:32.570
where they try to
aggregate that information

00:47:32.570 --> 00:47:34.502
in one place for people.

00:47:34.502 --> 00:47:36.460
AUDIENCE: Have you faced
any sort of resistance

00:47:36.460 --> 00:47:37.670
from the meat industry?

00:47:37.670 --> 00:47:41.600
Have there been any instances
of [INAUDIBLE] from them?

00:47:41.600 --> 00:47:43.160
NATHAN RUNKLE: No, they love me.

00:47:43.160 --> 00:47:46.490
[LAUGHTER]

00:47:46.490 --> 00:47:49.340
We're best friends.

00:47:49.340 --> 00:47:50.660
Yeah, I mean of course.

00:47:50.660 --> 00:47:52.230
So I think a number of things.

00:47:52.230 --> 00:47:56.650
One is they are trying
to make it a crime for us

00:47:56.650 --> 00:47:58.000
to do investigations.

00:47:58.000 --> 00:48:04.990
So around 2011, a new wave of
ag-gag bills were introduced.

00:48:04.990 --> 00:48:07.360
Agriculture gag
bills, a term coined

00:48:07.360 --> 00:48:10.780
by Mark Bittman, who was at "The
New York Times" at the time.

00:48:10.780 --> 00:48:13.030
These bills come
in three flavors.

00:48:13.030 --> 00:48:15.340
Some of them are outright
ban on video and photographs.

00:48:15.340 --> 00:48:17.020
Others relate to
job applications.

00:48:17.020 --> 00:48:19.090
Others relate to turning
all of your footage

00:48:19.090 --> 00:48:21.910
over to law enforcement
and no one else.

00:48:21.910 --> 00:48:24.760
But these have been heavily
pushed by the meat industry.

00:48:24.760 --> 00:48:28.310
And the dairy industry has
been very much behind them.

00:48:28.310 --> 00:48:34.210
So that's one of the big
pushbacks from the industry.

00:48:34.210 --> 00:48:36.860
But each company is
different, I will say.

00:48:36.860 --> 00:48:38.440
Every company is
run by individuals,

00:48:38.440 --> 00:48:39.790
so they have their own culture.

00:48:39.790 --> 00:48:42.550
And some companies,
including meat companies,

00:48:42.550 --> 00:48:44.050
when we've done
investigations, have

00:48:44.050 --> 00:48:47.810
responded by saying yes,
there is a problem here.

00:48:47.810 --> 00:48:49.450
Let's talk about
what some solutions

00:48:49.450 --> 00:48:53.200
are that we could implement,
that would make things better.

00:48:53.200 --> 00:48:56.230
So that is one outcome.

00:48:56.230 --> 00:48:59.500
Others, like Tyson,
and like Cargill,

00:48:59.500 --> 00:49:02.740
like I said, while they're
still doing horrible things

00:49:02.740 --> 00:49:06.750
for the animals they're
raising, are investing

00:49:06.750 --> 00:49:07.730
in these alternatives.

00:49:07.730 --> 00:49:08.380
Which is smart.

00:49:08.380 --> 00:49:10.421
You look at the energy
sector, and the smart ones

00:49:10.421 --> 00:49:11.800
are investing in green energy.

00:49:11.800 --> 00:49:15.550
You can either choose to
fight and change progress,

00:49:15.550 --> 00:49:18.710
or you can jump on board
and be a champion for it.

00:49:18.710 --> 00:49:21.620
So I think we're seeing
more and more of that.

00:49:21.620 --> 00:49:24.750
And I think that we'll
continue to see that trend.

00:49:24.750 --> 00:49:28.090
Again, these are companies
that really view themselves

00:49:28.090 --> 00:49:29.710
as protein companies.

00:49:29.710 --> 00:49:32.080
They're not in the business
of just torturing animals.

00:49:32.080 --> 00:49:34.570
That's the old way
of doing things,

00:49:34.570 --> 00:49:37.750
and they're doing
it as efficiently

00:49:37.750 --> 00:49:39.470
as they feel that they can.

00:49:39.470 --> 00:49:43.930
But I think that there really
won't be much of a choice

00:49:43.930 --> 00:49:45.980
but to move in this direction.

00:49:45.980 --> 00:49:49.230
The planet won't be able
to survive without it.

00:49:49.230 --> 00:49:51.530
AUDIENCE: So I have a
question from Menohar,

00:49:51.530 --> 00:49:54.375
what is being done to make
sure that Tyson, et cetera,

00:49:54.375 --> 00:49:57.440
will not gain enough shares
of these meatless ventures

00:49:57.440 --> 00:49:59.121
to prevent them from succeeding?

00:49:59.121 --> 00:50:01.120
Or to own the patents and
intellectual property,

00:50:01.120 --> 00:50:04.230
et cetera, or to negatively
control the activities

00:50:04.230 --> 00:50:06.450
of these ventures.

00:50:06.450 --> 00:50:09.450
NATHAN RUNKLE: Yeah,
that's a good question.

00:50:09.450 --> 00:50:11.100
So I'm not too
concerned about them

00:50:11.100 --> 00:50:13.110
trying to put these
places out of business.

00:50:13.110 --> 00:50:18.450
Again, I think the business
case for this is very strong.

00:50:18.450 --> 00:50:20.610
It can be far more efficient.

00:50:20.610 --> 00:50:22.350
So again, they're in
the protein space.

00:50:22.350 --> 00:50:24.690
They're not committed
to just continuing

00:50:24.690 --> 00:50:26.290
to slaughter animals.

00:50:26.290 --> 00:50:29.280
And if you look through
the history of, let's say,

00:50:29.280 --> 00:50:31.860
plant-based meat
alternatives, Gardein

00:50:31.860 --> 00:50:36.390
was recently purchased for
$150 million by Pinnacle Foods.

00:50:36.390 --> 00:50:39.090
That's actually increased
their distribution.

00:50:39.090 --> 00:50:42.360
That's actually gotten them into
more places, larger advertising

00:50:42.360 --> 00:50:43.650
budgets.

00:50:43.650 --> 00:50:45.330
We've seen this with lot of--

00:50:45.330 --> 00:50:47.739
Silk and other
dairy alternatives.

00:50:47.739 --> 00:50:49.530
They're being purchased
by dairy companies.

00:50:49.530 --> 00:50:52.200
And they're not trying to
shelve those, or push them away,

00:50:52.200 --> 00:50:54.840
they're actually
increasing their sales.

00:50:54.840 --> 00:50:56.350
These are for-profit businesses.

00:50:56.350 --> 00:50:58.590
They want to make money
where it can happen.

00:50:58.590 --> 00:51:03.360
So I'm not too
concerned about that.

00:51:03.360 --> 00:51:06.880
But the owners of those
companies, I'm sure,

00:51:06.880 --> 00:51:08.670
are keeping an eye on it.

00:51:08.670 --> 00:51:12.930
If you look at the innovators
in this space, many of them

00:51:12.930 --> 00:51:14.340
are mission driven.

00:51:14.340 --> 00:51:17.440
They want to help animals
and the environment, as well.

00:51:17.440 --> 00:51:19.565
AUDIENCE: How are you
working in the health area

00:51:19.565 --> 00:51:21.190
with information
that can help people

00:51:21.190 --> 00:51:25.220
stop eating meat without fear
of malnutrition, et cetera.

00:51:25.220 --> 00:51:27.690
NATHAN RUNKLE: Yes, and
this is a great question.

00:51:27.690 --> 00:51:31.440
We do touch some, on health.

00:51:31.440 --> 00:51:33.630
There's two approaches.

00:51:33.630 --> 00:51:36.447
We need to talk about the
why people should change

00:51:36.447 --> 00:51:38.280
their diet, but we also
need to equally talk

00:51:38.280 --> 00:51:40.380
about how people should
change their diet.

00:51:40.380 --> 00:51:42.030
Because if not, you
get a lot of people

00:51:42.030 --> 00:51:46.020
who agree in theory, that
plant-based eating is good,

00:51:46.020 --> 00:51:47.980
but they don't
know how to do it.

00:51:47.980 --> 00:51:49.920
So a lot of our
education work is

00:51:49.920 --> 00:51:53.516
done in providing people with
just the simple meal plans,

00:51:53.516 --> 00:51:55.140
and how to be healthy,
and all of that.

00:51:55.140 --> 00:51:57.810
So that's a big part
of those programs.

00:51:57.810 --> 00:51:59.910
We are an animal protection
organization, however,

00:51:59.910 --> 00:52:02.320
so we're not a health
care organization.

00:52:02.320 --> 00:52:04.080
So that's not our primary focus.

00:52:04.080 --> 00:52:06.630
That's not really where our
expertise and credibility

00:52:06.630 --> 00:52:07.380
comes in.

00:52:07.380 --> 00:52:09.390
But there are organizations
that are doing that,

00:52:09.390 --> 00:52:12.030
like Physicians Committee
for Responsible Medicine.

00:52:12.030 --> 00:52:14.400
There are incredible
resources and books,

00:52:14.400 --> 00:52:17.070
Dr. Gregor, "How Not to
Die," things like that.

00:52:17.070 --> 00:52:19.960
So we do direct people
in those ways as well.

00:52:22.680 --> 00:52:26.220
We want people on a
vegan diet to be healthy.

00:52:26.220 --> 00:52:29.760
Because you're going to be more
likely to stay with the diet.

00:52:29.760 --> 00:52:32.460
Recidivism is so
high with veganism.

00:52:32.460 --> 00:52:36.060
A lot of that is just
a social element.

00:52:36.060 --> 00:52:39.540
People don't realize the
social impact that going vegan

00:52:39.540 --> 00:52:40.270
can have.

00:52:40.270 --> 00:52:42.540
And so they want to get
back into the social graces

00:52:42.540 --> 00:52:44.020
of people.

00:52:44.020 --> 00:52:45.510
So that is part of what we do.

00:52:45.510 --> 00:52:47.010
People can go to
chooseveg.com, we

00:52:47.010 --> 00:52:49.630
have a lot of health
information there.

00:52:49.630 --> 00:52:51.770
AUDIENCE: Do you
have any pointers

00:52:51.770 --> 00:52:55.070
on how to talk to
kids, and specifically

00:52:55.070 --> 00:52:56.210
other people's children?

00:52:56.210 --> 00:52:57.710
Because kids usually
have questions,

00:52:57.710 --> 00:52:59.455
like, why don't you eat that.

00:52:59.455 --> 00:53:01.790
And the honest
answer of I don't eat

00:53:01.790 --> 00:53:04.569
cows is a very enlightening
experience for children.

00:53:04.569 --> 00:53:06.110
NATHAN RUNKLE: I
don't have any kids.

00:53:06.110 --> 00:53:12.440
I do have three nieces who are
all self-declared vegetarian

00:53:12.440 --> 00:53:16.860
or vegan, including my niece
Bella, who puts her allowance

00:53:16.860 --> 00:53:21.150
money towards a pig at Animal
Place that she's adopted.

00:53:21.150 --> 00:53:23.690
So she goes and sees this pig.

00:53:23.690 --> 00:53:27.920
Look, I think kids are much
brighter than a lot of people

00:53:27.920 --> 00:53:29.280
give them credit for.

00:53:29.280 --> 00:53:31.430
And I think that they can
understand these concepts

00:53:31.430 --> 00:53:34.620
much better than people
give them credit for.

00:53:34.620 --> 00:53:37.850
And I think that the
default for kids and humans

00:53:37.850 --> 00:53:40.820
is to be compassionate and
have empathy for animals.

00:53:40.820 --> 00:53:45.110
I don't think that I was
unique in my interest

00:53:45.110 --> 00:53:46.520
in animals growing up on a farm.

00:53:46.520 --> 00:53:50.360
In fact, I saw that with all
of my friends who were in 4H.

00:53:50.360 --> 00:53:53.540
And they would raise pigs
and cows for slaughter.

00:53:53.540 --> 00:53:55.400
And they would give
these animals names,

00:53:55.400 --> 00:53:56.840
and they would bottle
feed them, and they

00:53:56.840 --> 00:53:58.970
would stay up at night with
them if they were sick.

00:53:58.970 --> 00:54:01.940
And then they would sell them
by the pound to go to slaughter.

00:54:01.940 --> 00:54:04.100
And every single
one of those kids,

00:54:04.100 --> 00:54:06.830
essentially, was
heartbroken, and would cry,

00:54:06.830 --> 00:54:09.620
and would want to save
that animal that year.

00:54:09.620 --> 00:54:11.330
But then as the
years go on, they're

00:54:11.330 --> 00:54:13.880
just told that's the way it is.

00:54:13.880 --> 00:54:16.550
That's what these animals are
here for, we have to do this.

00:54:16.550 --> 00:54:18.800
And you could sort
of slowly see kids

00:54:18.800 --> 00:54:22.200
becoming desensitized and
changing their view on it.

00:54:22.200 --> 00:54:28.460
So I don't have, really,
specific advice on this,

00:54:28.460 --> 00:54:31.880
but I think it needs to be
appropriate given the age.

00:54:31.880 --> 00:54:35.150
I think really young
kids, we probably

00:54:35.150 --> 00:54:37.490
can talk to them in a
way that doesn't involve

00:54:37.490 --> 00:54:40.060
gory slaughterhouse footage.

00:54:40.060 --> 00:54:41.790
And that would probably
go over better.

00:54:41.790 --> 00:54:46.160
But I think that we can
talk to kids about animals

00:54:46.160 --> 00:54:47.330
having personalities.

00:54:47.330 --> 00:54:50.900
And if they have a dog or
a cat, that pigs and cows

00:54:50.900 --> 00:54:52.290
are exactly the same.

00:54:52.290 --> 00:54:54.500
I think they can
understand that concept

00:54:54.500 --> 00:54:56.690
I think it becomes challenging
when parents aren't

00:54:56.690 --> 00:54:59.870
supportive of that, because
then you have kids that get it,

00:54:59.870 --> 00:55:04.310
but they can't get food if
their parents aren't supportive.

00:55:04.310 --> 00:55:07.340
And that way, I think
it's important to have

00:55:07.340 --> 00:55:10.940
meaningful conversations
with parents as well.

00:55:10.940 --> 00:55:18.380
And encourage them to support
the children's curiosity

00:55:18.380 --> 00:55:19.520
about this.

00:55:19.520 --> 00:55:25.770
But that's easier said than
done, perhaps, sometimes.

00:55:25.770 --> 00:55:26.820
AUDIENCE: Hi.

00:55:26.820 --> 00:55:28.460
This question isn't
really for me.

00:55:28.460 --> 00:55:32.349
I've been vegetarian,
or vegan, for 30 years.

00:55:32.349 --> 00:55:33.140
NATHAN RUNKLE: Wow.

00:55:33.140 --> 00:55:36.285
AUDIENCE: I think it's just,
it's been awesome for me.

00:55:36.285 --> 00:55:39.650
I have great energy.

00:55:39.650 --> 00:55:41.070
It's been amazing.

00:55:41.070 --> 00:55:43.210
Clean meat, I
would never eat it.

00:55:43.210 --> 00:55:44.210
I would never try it.

00:55:44.210 --> 00:55:45.450
I don't miss meat.

00:55:45.450 --> 00:55:47.360
I don't want to ever have meat.

00:55:47.360 --> 00:55:51.060
But what are the ethical
dimensions, maybe

00:55:51.060 --> 00:55:55.460
for some people who are
vegetarian or vegan?

00:55:55.460 --> 00:55:56.960
NATHAN RUNKLE: Yeah.

00:55:56.960 --> 00:56:00.830
Well, personally, I don't
care if vegetarians or vegans

00:56:00.830 --> 00:56:01.730
eat clean meat.

00:56:01.730 --> 00:56:04.100
It's really not for
vegetarians or vegans.

00:56:04.100 --> 00:56:08.120
So if you're a happy
vegetarian or vegan,

00:56:08.120 --> 00:56:11.480
and you want to eat beans,
nuts, legumes, awesome.

00:56:11.480 --> 00:56:13.490
Continue to do it.

00:56:13.490 --> 00:56:18.770
I think clean meat is really
about the 98% of Americans,

00:56:18.770 --> 00:56:21.110
and people around the globe,
that aren't vegetarian.

00:56:21.110 --> 00:56:22.820
That don't want to
become vegetarian.

00:56:22.820 --> 00:56:25.040
That want to
continue to eat meat.

00:56:25.040 --> 00:56:29.010
So that's kind of my take on it.

00:56:29.010 --> 00:56:33.020
I'm not here to try to
convince vegans to eat it.

00:56:33.020 --> 00:56:35.990
I want meat eaters to eat it.

00:56:35.990 --> 00:56:37.850
Yeah.

00:56:37.850 --> 00:56:39.830
Thank you everyone,
so much for spending

00:56:39.830 --> 00:56:41.030
your afternoon with me.

00:56:41.030 --> 00:56:44.380
